2011/1/8 sergio <mailbox@sergio.spb.ru>

> Hello.
>
> Is it possible, to control ~ substitution?
> When I type 'echo ~' I get '/home/sergio' --- all right.
> When I type 'echo a~b' I get 'a~b' --- all right.
> Also sh and bash do the same.
>
> But when I type 'echo h=3D~' (or h=3D~sergio, or h=3D~/some/path) I get '=
h=3D~'.
> sh does the same, and bash will out 'h=3D/home/sergio'.
>
> How to control this? Why this may be bad? May be this is a bug?
>

Hi,

Try 'setopt magicequalsubst'.


man zshexpn:
[=E2=80=A6]
FILENAME EXPANSION
    Each  word is checked to see if it begins with an unquoted `~'.
[=E2=80=A6]
  Notes
    Filename  expansion is performed on the right hand side of a parameter
    assignment, including those appearing after commands  of  the  typeset
    family.
[=E2=80=A6]
    If the option MAGIC_EQUAL_SUBST is set, any unquoted shell argument in
    the  form  `identifier=3Dexpression' becomes eligible for file expansio=
n
    as described in the previous paragraph.  Quoting the  first  `=3D'  als=
o
    inhibits this.
[=E2=80=A6]


Guillaume

